<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Reinstates Trade Powers Against Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203200194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1808 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 2 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton has decided to sign an executive order reviving his 
broad legal authority to impose trade sanctions against Japan, 
it was reported here today. 
  THE NEW YORK TIMES quoted senior U.S. officials as saying 
the 
President had accepted the recommendation from his economic 
advisers that he reinstate by executive order the "Super 301" 
trade retaliation mechanism. 
  Since the U.S.-Japan summit meeting failed to reach a trade 
agreement two weeks ago, the U.S. Administration has been 
considering measures to compel Japan to open markets for U.S. 
products. 
  "Super 301", passed by Congress in 1988, requires the U.S. 
trade representatives to identify the countries that maintain 
the most egregious trade barriers and to use the legislation to 
eliminate those barriers. 
  If an offending country refuses to eliminate the specific 
barriers, the U.S. president has the authority to retaliate by 
blocking an equivalent amount of that country's exports to the 
United States. 
  These officials said the President still intended to move 
cautiously and simply signing the executive order did not mean 
that he would use it against Japan immediately. 
  But some analysts argued that putting such a powerful weapon 
into place could mark a dangerous increase in U.S.-Japan trade 
tensions. 
  Reacting to THE NEW YORK TIME's report, a spokesman of 
Japanese Government said today that such a move would be 
"counterproductive" and urged the United States to use a 
"sensible" approach to the trade question. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

