<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegates to Asian Population, Development Meeting Arrive </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203210194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1352 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 2 (XINHUA) -- Parliamentarians, 
experts and scholars from 14 Asian countries arrived here today 
on separate occasions to attend the 10th Asian parliamentarians' 
meeting on population and development, scheduled to open 
tomorrow. 
  The participants including representatives of the United 
Nations and other international organizations will also take 
part in the second session of the fourth executive committee of 
the Asian Forum of Parliamentarians on Population and 
Development (AFPPD). 
  The 10th Asian parliamentarians' meeting on population and 
development will be held according to a proposal made by the 
executive committee of the AFPPD at its fourth meeting held in 
Kuala Lumpur, capital of Malaysia, last October. 
  This is also the first meeting to be held in China sponsored 
by the Asian Population and Development Association (APDA). 
  The meeting is aimed at further enhancing exchanges and 
cooperation on population among parliamentarians of these 
countries. 
  The main topics of the two-day meeting are about the issue 
of 
population and development and women in the 21st century -- 
strategy for prosperity and peace. 
  Zhao Dongwan, leader of the delegation of China's National 
People's Congress (NPC) and chairman of the NPC Education, 
Science, Culture and Public Health Committee, will address the 
meeting at the opening ceremony. 
  Since its founding in 1982, the APDA has provided financial 
aid to meetings of the AFPPD. It also sponsored nine Asian 
parliamentarians' meetings on population and development, all of 
which were attended by delegations from the NPC. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

