<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Secretary of State Cited on Deepening Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303060694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0527 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 2 (XINHUA) -- Relations between 
the United States and China entered a new phase last September, 
according to U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher who said 
President Clinton had directed him to develop a broader set of 
relationships with China. 
  The U.S. secretary of state made the remarks this afternoon 
in the U.S. State Department during an interview with Chinese, 
Japanese, Australian and South Korean reporters, on the eve of 
his departure for a 10-day trip to Australia, Japan and China 
which begins March 4. 
  "That new relationship is symbolized most importantly by 
President Clinton's meeting with China's President Jiang Zemin 
in Seattle last November," Christopher stressed. 
  He said that he met with China's foreign minister last 
September in New York following Clinton's directive and the two 
countries agreed to develop a broader set of relationships. 
  That resulted in U.S. Secretary of Finance Lloyd Bentsen, 
U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor and U.S. Secretary of 
Agriculture Mike Espy meeting with or having contact with 
high-level officials from China. 
  "At the same time we sought to deepen our relations as we 
are 
two prominent and great nations with tremendous resources," 
added Christopher. "It's important we have more communications 
so that we understand each other's viewpoints and problems." 
  He said that he is looking forward to meeting with Chinese 
Foreign Minister Qian and discussing a full range of topics 
which would include security, political and international 
issues, trade, non-proliferation and human rights. 
  At the end of his fourth 10-day Asian trip Christopher will 
proceed to Vladivostok to meet with Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev to discuss developments in the Balkans as well as 
the tension created over the arrest of a CIA official who 
allegedly spied for Russia. 
  Christopher also answered reporters' questions concerning 
U.S.-Japan trade and the situation on the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

