<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brittan Says Discrimination Against UK `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0103152694 London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH in English 1 Mar 94 
p 12 </F>

<F P=103> PM0103152694 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Graham Hutchings report: "British Firms Must Not Be </F>
Blacked, EC Tells China"] 
  [Text] Any attempt by China to punish British firms in its 
row over political reform in Hong Kong would be "completely 
unacceptable" to Europe, Sir Leon Brittan, European Trade 
Commissioner, said yesterday. 
  In a sharp exchange with Wu Yi, China's Foreign Trade 
Minister, during a press conference in Beijing, Sir Leon said: 
"Any action that discriminated against one member state on 
political grounds would be a very serious matter -- not just for 
that country, but for the European Union as a whole. 
  "I want to make quite clear that the foundation of the 
relationship between the European Union as a whole and China is 
one of non-discrimination." 
  When Wu jokingly suggested that Sir Leon had issued his 
warning because he was a Briton, he replied this had "nothing to 
do with it. 
  "I speak as the commissioner whose task it is to represent 
the interests of the European Union as a whole. And if Madame 
Wu doesn't fully appreciate that, I'm glad to make it clear now." 
  He did not say how Brussels might react to any 
discrimination. But Community officials have hinted they could 
take retaliatory action against China, which runs a big trade 
surplus with Europe. 
  Sir Leon, visiting Beijing to discuss various trade issues, 
was responding to remarks by Wu that suggested the row over 
democratic reform plans in Hong Kong would inevitably affect 
Sino-British trade. British businessmen have been concerned by 
China's threats to exclude firms from lucrative contracts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

