<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Local XINHUA Officials React Cautiously to `94 Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0303071194 Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO in Chinese 3 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0303071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Zheng Guoxiong Pointed Out That </F>
Financial Arrangements Must Keep Expenditures Within the Limits 
of Revenue; Zhang Junsheng Doubted Whether Hong Kong Government 
Could Honor Its Repeated Promise of Keeping More Reserves For 
the Government of the Special Administrative Region, SAR"] 
  [Text] Zheng Guoxiong, deputy director of the Hong Kong 
branch of the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY, said yesterday: We have just 
received the Hong Kong Government's financial budget proposal 
but have not yet been able to study it. However, he stated: 
Financial arrangements must uphold the principle of "keeping 
expenditures within the limits of revenue." 
  He said: Financial arrangements should be given a long-term 
consideration and are not something that can be accomplished in 
a year. The Hong Kong Government must give consideration to its 
operations for the next several years. Should anything 
unexpected happen, it must have fully adequate financial 
reserves to cope with the situation. Moreover, the Hong Kong 
Government must also consider that, after the reversion of 
sovereignty, there must be a basic convergence financially as 
well as a sizable amount of reserves to enable the Hong Kong 
economy to continue to expand. 
  Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of the Hong Kong Branch of 
the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY, said: Yesterday afternoon, we received 
the Hong Kong Government's financial budget proposal for the new 
financial year. This is represents a change the previous 
practice of giving the document to the agency only after the 
financial budget proposal was made public. He stated: If the 
Hong Kong Government has a financial surplus and is willing to 
leave it to the SAR Government, we will suggest that the 
government sign something to show its commitment. He said: 
Every year the Hong Kong Government remarks that it is leaving 
large quantities of reserves. He expressed the hope that the 
Hong Kong Government could effectively implement its statements. 
  Moreover, he said: It is hoped that the Hong Kong Government 
will leave 25 billion [no currency specified] in financial 
reserves to the SAR Government in accordance with the Memorandum 
of Understanding on the new airport. 

</TEXT>

