<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Official Accuses British Side of Debt Shifting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0203130094 Beijing XINHUA Hong Kong Service in Chinese 
1032 GMT 28 feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0203130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Hong Kong Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, 28 February (XINHUA)--Zhu Yucheng, 
deputy director of the Hong Kong Branch of the XINHUA News 
Agency, criticized the British Hong Kong Government for changing 
the Airport Authority into an airport corporation, with an aim 
to shifting the debts for the construction of the new airport to 
the future special administration government. 
  When attending a soiree yesterday, Zhu Yucheng said: On the 
new airport issue, the Chinese side has all along acted in 
accordance with the Memorandum of Understanding on the new 
airport, but the British side has delayed for a long time before 
advancing its fourth financial proposal. There is still a big 
problem with the proposal, that is, who will actually bear the 
debt amounting to 23 billion Hong Kong dollars or so? The 
British Hong Kong Government intends to turn the Airport 
Authority into a so-called "corporation," saying that the debts 
will be shifted to the "corporation" in the future. However, the 
behind-the-scenes backer of the "corporation" is the Hong Kong 
Government. Like the Mass Transit Railway Corporation, the 
corporation is fully funded by the Hong Kong Government. 
Therefore, superficially, the new airport's debts are shifted to 
the "corporation" but at the end, they will be borne by the 
future special administrative region government and will be all 
shifted to the compatriots in Hong Kong. 
  Zhu Yucheng pointed out: The objective of the Britons before 
quitting Hong Kong is very clear. Economically, grabbing the 
maximum benefits and politically, making arrangements for their 
group [ban zi 3803 1311], in an attempt to compel the special 
administrative region government to accept it and thus exercise 
British rule without the Britons. He hoped that the Hong Kong 
people would cast away illusions and no longer expect that a 
colonialist official could leave anything good for them. 
British officials can only grab the maximum benefits for the 
British side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

