<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPC Plenary Session Calls For Efforts to Fight Corruption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103142394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1259 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 1 (XINHUA) -- The third plenary 
session of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of 
the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) issued a communique here 
today, calling for unremitting efforts to combat and root out 
corruption. 
  The anticorruption campaign must be firmly and more 
effectively carried out, so as to maintain social stability and 
guarantee the progress of reforms, opening up and economic 
growth, said the communique, issued at the end of the six-day 
session. 
  "The anticorruption drive is long, arduous and urgent and it 
is necessary to carry out a protracted struggle against 
corruption and to score successes in different periods," the 
communique pointed out. 
  While affirming the achievements already made in the 
anticorruption campaign, the communique noted that negative and 
corrupt phenomena still persist and in some cases are quite 
serious. No efforts should be spared in the crackdown on 
corruption, it urged. 
  The communique said that the decision by the CPC Central 
Committee and the State Council on launching the anticorruption 
struggle is correct and has guaranteed the smooth progress of 
the fight against corruption. 
  Marked results have been achieved in the anticorruption 
campaign since the convening of the second plenary session of 
the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection (CCDI) last 
August, with the dwindling of some corruptive phenomena, the 
communique said. 
  During the session, 103 members of CCDI carefully studied an 
important speech made by Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the 
CPC Central Committee, on renewed efforts against corruption. 
  The speech, which called for the investigation and severe 
punishment of serious cases, is of great significance in guiding 
the anticorruption drive in the new situation and is a clear 
indication of the determination of the CPC to wipe out 
corruption, the communique said. 
  At the session, which was presided over by CCDI Secretary 
Wei 
Jianxing, five new requirements were set for leading officials 
to maintain clarity and honesty in performing their duties. 
  The communique also called on leading cadres to take a lead 
in fighting corruption. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

