<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangzhou's Inflation `Higher' Than Last Year's 19 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0303023894 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 0811 
GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0303023894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, 20 Feb (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN 
SHE)--Guangzhou's January inflation rate exceeded 19 percent, 
exhibiting greater inflationary pressures than last year. 
  While he refrained from stating the specific inflation rate 
for January in an interview with a reporter yesterday, an 
authoritative official at the department concerned in the 
Guangzhou City government said: "It is certainly a little 
higher than last January's 19 percent." The precise figure is 
not known until it is released by the relevant government 
department, he said. 
  The official said that the Guangzhou market was relatively 
stable in the Spring Festival period. 
  But this official is concerned about preset price increases 
in Guangzhou. He said that pork recently went up by 23 or 24 or 
even 30 yuan per jin from an original price of less than 20, 
adding that such unreasonable rises are unacceptable to citizens. 
  The government's new task is to exercise effective price 
controls while freeing prices, he continued. [sentence as 
received] 
  Guangzhou's inflation rate in 1993 was as high as 25.1 
percent, ranking third among other areas across the country. 
  Guangzhou Deputy Mayor Chen Kaizhi stressed here two days 
ago 
that Guangzhou's inflation rate must be kept below 15 percent 
this year. 

</TEXT>

