<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rural Hubei Living Conditions Improve </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303014894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0113 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303014894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, March 3 (XINHUA) -- Living conditions for 
rural residents in central China's Hubei Province have improved 
greatly over the past 15 years, according to a recent survey 
carried out in rural areas of the province. 
  The survey says that the per capita living space for rural 
residents increased from 11.8 sq m in 1978 to 25 sq m in 1993. 
Seventy percent of the newly-built houses are made of bricks and 
timber or bricks and concrete. 
  In Yunyang Prefecture of northwestern Hubei, more than 
14,000 
rural households have moved into newly-built houses from caves, 
shabby thatched shacks, or endangered houses. 
  The city government of Enshi, in southwestern Hubei, 
earmarked funds for helping to build new houses to move its last 
group of 400 rural households who used to live in caves. 
  Many new villages for fishermen, as well as a large number 
of 
house-boats made of cement, have been built in many of the 
province's lake areas, helping more and more fishermen settle 
down in fixed abodes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

