<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangsu's Nanjing Develops Into `Major Economic Center' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203095494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0730 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nanjing, March 2 (XINHUA) -- Nanjing, capital of 
east China's Jiangsu Province, has developed into a major 
economic center second only to Shanghai in the middle and lower 
reaches of the Chang Jiang River. 
  The city has formed an economic and co-operative network 
involving the fields of transportation, trade, banking and 
information with Shanghai, Wuhan (capital of Hubei Province), 
Chongqing in Sichuan Province, Hefei (capital of Anhui Province) 
and Nanchang (capital of Jiangxi Province). 
  Meanwhile, the city's markets for capital goods and 
international futures have become regional transaction centers. 
  With convenient transportation facilities, Nanjing is 
regarded by major world consortiums and research institutions as 
a city with a promising future. 
  Wang Wulong, acting mayor of the city, said Nanjing is 
improving its urban functions. 
  It has opened 430 professional markets and trading centers, 
and markets of finance, technology and labor service. Their 
annual transaction volume tops 10 billion yuan. 
  One of the major cities in the Chang Jiang River Valley, 
Nanjing has opened four container shipping routes to Japan, Hong 
Kong, Singapore and the Middle East, respectively. Its annual 
handling capacity reaches more than 50 million tons at present, 
and is expected to top 100 million tons by the end of this 
century. 
  At present, Nanjing's 1,000 financial organizations are 
doing 
business with some 200 banking organizations in over 40 
countries and regions. 
  In addition, the city is developing a number of credit and 
trust, securities, financial and international leasing companies 
to pave the way for the setting up of banking organizations in 
the middle and lower reaches of the Chang Jiang River Valley. 
  A survey shows that Nanjing has approved the establishment 
of 
2,600 foreign-funded enterprises from more than 40 countries and 
regions so far. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1990 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi042_o_94003" </HT>


