<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   People's Bank of China To Fund Inland Rural Enterprises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203064394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0632 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 2 (XINHUA) -- China has decided to 
step up the development of rural enterprises in its inland 
provinces as part of an effort to narrow the gap between their 
economy and that of coastal regions. 
  The country's central bank, the People's Bank of China, will 
allocate special funds every year till the year 2000 as low 
interest loans for these areas to develop township enterprises. 
  This was revealed here today by He Kang, vice-chairman of 
the 
Chinese Association for Science and Technology (CAST) at a CAST 
national conference. 
  They will also be given priority in using other loans from 
banks, or encouraged to raise funds through issuing shares, said 
the vice- chairman, who was formerly minister of agriculture. 
  Economic and technological cooperation between the inland 
provinces and coastal regions is to be enhanced in terms of 
selling of technology, jointly venturing and raw material 
processing, he said. 
  Other programs include developing rural towns and trade with 
bordering countries, he disclosed. 
  "Though these places suffer from the inconvenience of 
transportation, they have a long border line, on which they may 
rely to enter foreign markets," He Kang said. 
  "With both foreign markets and home markets accessible, the 
inland provinces could better allocate resources." 
  But the rural enterprises in the inland provinces, covering 
80 percent of China's territory and having 65 percent of the 
country's 800 million farmers, get a smaller slice of the cake 
than their coastal counterparts. 
  He Kang said that the inland areas have advantages of rich 
natural resources, abundant labor and considerable market 
potential. 
  "With support by the central government, aid from the 
eastern 
areas and avid expectations of their people, the rural 
enterprises in the inland provinces will be quickly developed 
and the whole economy will step further," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

